A lambda is <i>usually</i> passed as a generic argument, because that&#x27;s the only way to avoid virtual dispatch (and the only way to take a lambda by-value without allocation), but you can also use trait objects if you want:<p><pre><code>  fn foo(x: &Fn(i32)) {
      x(5);
  }

  fn main() {
      foo(&|x| println!(&quot;x: {}&quot;, x));
  }
</code></pre>
Or you can use std::boxed::FnBox in order to take a Box<FnBox(i32)> but that&#x27;s currently marked as unstable (it exists because you can&#x27;t take Box<FnOnce(..)> as you can&#x27;t move out of the box in order to call the lambda as it does not have a statically-known size, but if you&#x27;re ok taking Fn or FnMut then you don&#x27;t need it).

You can also pass a fn to a function that takes a closure.<p><pre><code>    fn foo<T: FnOnce(i32)>(x: T) {
        x(5);
    }

    fn bar(_: i32) {
        println!(&quot;Bar&quot;);
    }

    fn main() {
        foo(bar);
    }</code></pre>
